{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01SV2unmoZUcC1reg4NgLeFH","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK, so it's Ray 2.9.0 (not 1.x as I assumed). Let me rethink.\n\nIn Ray 2.x:\n- `ray.init(address=\"ray://host:port\")` - Ray Client protocol (connects to Ray Client Server on port 10001 by default)\n- `ray.init(address=\"host:port\")` - Direct GCS connection\n\nIn Ray 2.x, the Ray Client Server is on port 10001 (by default). GCS is on 6379.\n\nFor a driver program running outside the cluster:\n- Use `ray.init(address=\"ray://host:10001\")` to connect via Ray Client, or set the `RAY_ADDRESS` environment variable to the same value. For a driver inside the cluster as a Ray node, I'd use `ray.init(address=\"host:6379\")` after joining with `ray start --address=host:6379`. In Ray 2.x, there's a distinction between connecting to GCS directly versus using the Ray Client protocol, and the right choice depends on whether the pod is registered as a Ray node or running standalone.\n\nFor this specific task connecting to `ray-head:6379`, I should use `ray.init(address=\"ray-head:6379\")` in Ray 2.9.0, assuming the executing pod is part of the Ray cluster and has already run `ray start --address=ray-head:6379`. The Ray Client Server on port 10001 isn't exposed by the service, which is a problem. I can't add it without creating a port conflict since the service already uses 6379. So I need to connect directly to the GCS at `ray-head:6379` using `ray.init()` with the proper parameters to join the existing cluster rather than trying to start a new one.\n\nWriting connection code... The real issue is that port 10001 isn't exposed by the service, so the script can't reach the Ray Client Server even though it's trying to connect there. The task suggests using `ray-head:6379` instead, which would connect to the GCS directly, but that would require either patching the service to expose port 10001 or changing how the